The workshop was successfully held in association with the International Conference on Advanced Learning Teachnologies at the University of Texas in Austin, Texas, July 25-28, 2016. All of the invited mentees and mentors were present and actively participated. Subsequent video-conferences were held and invidivual mentees and mentors continued collaboration via email and other means subsequent to the workshop. Two of the mentees collaborated with a mentor on another project after the meeting, and two others are still collaborating with mentors.
Major goals, objectives and outcomes included the following:

Established a professional and social network between mentees and mentors (clearly achieved);
Supported early career faculty and doctoral students in developing viable short- and long-term research agendas (feedback from mentees strongly suggests this was achieved);
Provided feedback to mentees about their research agendas (designed in to the meetings in Austin);
Expanded and strengthened the cyberlearning community (hard to measure &ndash; but all believe that has been achieved as the ICALT 2017 doctoral consortium is being modeled after the successful 2016 meeting).


Subsequent ICALT meetings are being modeled after this early career workshop. One mentee has a book in print based on feedback received. Several others are continuing to collaborate with t hier mentors nearly a year after the worskhop.

